public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // The approach is to use logarithms. If log3(n) is an integer, then n is a power of three.
        // However, we cannot directly use log base 3 in Java, so we change the base using the
        // change of base formula: log3(n) = log10(n) / log10(3)
        // We need to check if the result of this division is an integer.

        // First, we check if n is less than 1 because powers of three are positive and nonzero.
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }

        // Use Math.log10() to calculate the log base 10 and check if the result is an integer.
        return Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(3) % 1 == 0;
    }
}
```

This code snippet defines a class `Solution` with a method `isPowerOfThree` that takes an integer `n` and returns `true` if it is a power of three, otherwise `false`. The check is done using logarithms to avoid the need for loops or recursion. It checks if the division of the logarithm of `n` base 10 by the logarithm of 3 base 10 results in a whole number. If it does, `n` is a power of three.

